ce:section.ce:para:
Considering the excellent chemical reactivity and fine-tuning ability, ILs-mediated synthesis of rare-earth luminescence advanced functional materials has drawn considerable attention from the scientific communities where ILs are used as a matrix. A.V. Mudring et al. [41] developed lanthanide-doped LaF3 phosphors in the nanoscale range using ILs as a synthetic matrix. It was shown that tiny nano phosphor particles of 6–8 nm size; create bright white light visible to the bare eye. By adjusting the λexc

                     . and dopant ion concentrations, it was possible to fine-tune the emission colors from blue to yellow, crossing white light very similar to typical D65 daylight. However, there aren't many photonic applications of ILs-integrated lanthanide-doped hybrid materials because it's difficult to use ILs in solid-state optoelectronic devices because of their fluidity while maintaining their distinctive features. Surprisingly, it is possible to polymerize ILs to create a polymeric chain where the ions are somehow held tightly yet retain their distinct properties. Doping the lanthanide complexes into the lengthy chain of this kind of polymer is an easy technique to create the ILs-assimilated lanthanide hybrid material. Li and colleagues developed [42] and produced several unique PILs, including lanthanide hybrid resources, POSS-PVIM@ [Ln(DBM)3] (Ln = Eu, Tb, Gd), by copolymerizing POSS with [Ln(DBM)3] @PVIM-PA (Scheme 3
                     ) which are lanthanide functionalized ILs and characterized by various analytical methods. First, the nucleophilic substitution of bromo aromatic with imidazole occurs due to the attack of lone pair of N atoms on the carbon having a good leaving group –Br of bormo aromatic compounds. Subsequently, coordination of lanthanide followed by copolymerization obtained [Ln(DBM)3]@PVIM-PA. Both POSS-PVIM @ [Eu(DBM)3] and POSS-PVIM @ [Tb(DBM)3] display the typical centre ion emission, proving that POSS-PVIM could successfully sensitize Eu3+ and Tb3+. When the ratios of the other three lanthanide cations (Eu3+, Tb3+, and Gd3+) are 1:3:3, the PL color can be adjusted to white light. Furthermore, a PL film showing uniformity and transparency with high-power light and thermal stability was also demonstrated. These are possible only due to the long-chain structure of this polymer and POSS's rigid skeleton. These findings generate a novel and exciting path for the community of materials chemists to plan and fabricate multi-component, photoresponsive PILs integrated hybrid lanthanide functional resources, which may have potential use in versatile optoelectronic device systems.

Huang and colleagues [66] recently synthesized and studied [Bmim]2SbCl5, an antimony-based PL ILs that emit bright yellow and white light, having QY of up to 86.3% when exposed to UV radiation. PL properties of [Bmim]2SbCl5, ILs could be fine-tuned by varying the λexc. The chromaticity coordinates are (0.409, 0.411), (0.376, 0.375), and (0.483, 0.489) when the [Bmim]2SbCl5, ILs were excited at 285 nm, 303 nm, and 368 nm, respectively (Fig. 3
                     ). The point (0.376, 0.375) lies within the white-light color spectrum, while the other two are all located in the yellow color space. The [Bmim]2SbCl5 ILs emission colors, which range from yellow to white, could be fine-tuned by changing the λexc
                     . More importantly, this research suggests a new path for producing effective ILs-based PL materials by mixing distinct MXn anions (M = main group metal ion, X = halogen) with different imidazolium cations.

Yan and coworkers [100] created reusable plastic 1-14 pH indicator strips based on the excellent anion-exchanging properties of PILs. These pH-responsive PILs-based dyes are produced through the anion-exchange reaction of anionic dyes such as CR, TB, BG, and MO with imidazolium-based PILs (Scheme 11
                     ). The pH-responsive color variations on these pH-detecting strips are improved, and pH responsiveness is reversible in both aqueous and non-aqueous solutions (Fig. 6
                     ). The hydrophobic PILs-based acid-base sensors using MO as an acid and MB as a base indicator were subsequently designed and developed by Xia et al. [101] that could be employed from a wide range of solvents to examine their acid-base indicative natures. Fig. 7
                      demonstrates the acidochromism and UV-visible spectral behavior of PIL-MO–MB in CH2Cl2 due to the addition of Ac and IPA as representative examples of acid and base. A proton-responsive dye ionogel based on BMIMTf2N, BMIMMO, and PMMA was fabricated by Taubert et al., [102] which exhibits a strong and reversible colorimetric change in the presence of protons or hydroxide ions from aqueous to the non-aqueous medium.

An intense blue photoluminescent ILs based on PAMAM dendrimer was reported by Dai et al. in 2005 [172]. Subsequently, several fluorophoric ILs based on benzobis(imidazolium) cation, along with their photophysical behavior, was demonstrated by Bielawski and co-workers [154] (Fig. 17
                     ). Again, a series of anthracene-based imidazolium photoluminescent salt was prepared by Dyson and co-workers [173]. The PL properties of these salts depend on the nature of counter anions. However, ILs based on quinolizinium cation with extremely high QYs with bright cyan PL were reported by Deng et al. in 2011 [174]. In the same year, solvent dependence and aggregation-induced enhanced emission behavior of some amphiphilic anthracene salts with the variation of counter anions were demonstrated by Kohmoto co-workers [175]. Multicolor PL from a series of tripodal quinolinium, pyridinium, and pyridium salts was achieved by Kato et al. in 2012 by fine-tuning the electron-donating and electron-withdrawing abilities of functional groups covering the visible spectrum from blue-green to red. [176] Further, they developed [177] the high luminescent oxadiazole-based columnar liquid crystals with a diethanolamine moiety based on intramolecular donor-acceptor charge transfer. The co-assembly of these oxadiazole-based derivatives through hydrogen bonding leads to the formation of thermally stable nanosegregated columnar structures confined in the channels of ILs, and intense PL from light blue to blue-green was achieved. ILs containing various prototropic forms of FL were prepared by Ermelinda's co-workers [178], and details of photophysical properties were also investigated. Ravoo and Li et al. fabricated a novel class of optical spheres with various distinctive properties by combining several PILs with various anions and spherical colloidal crystals [179]. These spheres could serve as functional microspheres that could mimic the main properties of real molecules. A series of high photoluminescent salicylate ILs and their color-tunable properties were also demonstrated by Mudring et al. [180]. Several azobenzene-based photoresponsive ILs and light-modulating aggregation behaviors were demonstrated by Jianji et al. [181]
                     . Subsequently, they also explored reversible conductivity modulating properties of azobenzene ILs, having some interesting features for the design and development of microscale photocontrol devices [182]. A blue emissive carbazole-based GUMBOS with excellent fluorescence properties and photo- and thermal stability having potential for the fabrication of OLEDs was reported by Warner and co-workers [65]. Ionic liquidation was used by Deng et al. [155] to produce liquid luminous compounds successfully. They have produced several ionic liquidized naphthalene sulphonamides to create a new class of innovative FLMS materials. The majority of the salts are liquids at normal temperatures. Under 365 nm UV light irradiation, most FLMSs exhibit green PL features in both the solution and pure liquid states. However, Avó et al. [171] reported two ILs with photoisomerizable p-hydroxycinnamic acid and their photochemistry in solution and neat conditions. It was revealed that upon irradiation with light, the absorption maxima are changed, attributed to the reversible trans-cis photoisomerization, resulting in a significant reduction of melting points of the ILs obtained through DSC measurements. By combining a phosphonium cation with the well-known fluorescent dye ANS, Laia et al. [183] developed intrinsic luminous ILs in 2015. The pure product was obtained as a dark black and viscous RTIL displaying blue PL under UV light having CIE values x=0.198, y=0.321. The luminescence property is sensitive to temperature due to its high viscosity. ILs relaxations are slow, revealed from the time-dependent dynamic Stokes’ shift measurement. A highly luminous ILs based on a dansylamide chromophore was introduced by Zhang and co-workers [184] that emits high intense greenish emission under UV light irradiation and employed for the identification explosive nitroaromatic compounds. A TTP2BTB-based ILs was prepared and employed to detect and identify organic solvents and a mixture of such solvents colorimetrically [185]. Fiorani et al. [186] developed a straightforward and highly synthetic route for synthesizing a library of novel luminescent ILs in 2015 based on tryptophan (Trp), phenylalanine (Phe), and glycine-glycine functionalized dipeptide having phosphonium and ammonium cation containing moieties and dansylated amino acids as counter anions. Additionally, under conventional laboratory circumstances, the produced RTILs are all liquids and exhibit the expected luminous behavior of dansyl-based chromophores in both solution and plain liquid phases. However, from the perspective of fundamental and scientific applications, the light modulation self-assembly behavior of ILs in an aqueous solution is extremely important. In view of these facts, Wang et al. [187] created and characterized a novel family of light-responsive ILs made up of trans-cinnamic acid ([CA]) as an anion and [Cnmim]+ (n = 4, 6, 8, 10, 12). UV light's modulation action was carried out to investigate the aggregation behavior of the synthesized ILs in an aqueous solution. The percentage of cis-isomer of these ILs was determined from photoisomerism equilibrium with the help of HPLC measurements. The aggregation behavior of [Cnmim][CA] (n = 8, 10, and 12) was found to be effectively controlled by UV light in an aqueous medium. However, Nobuoka et al. [188] showed that ILs could be photoisomerized using azobenzene moieties in 2016. A reversible solid-to-liquid phase change brought by photo- and thermal stimulation was seen in ILs that contain p, p-azobenzene or o,p-tetrafluoroazobenzene moiety. They demonstrated that the liquid cis-p,p azo isomer was produced by photoisomerization of the linear trans p, p-azoisomer, which is solid at ambient temperature. The glass transitions temperature is slightly lowered following photoisomerization, and the bent trans-o, p-azoisomer is a liquid at ambient temperature. However, Chen and his team [189] developed a novel method for synthesizing branched alkyl chains into π-conjugated, photoluminescent RTILs (Scheme 15
                     ). They demonstrated that the attachment of the branched alkyl chains adjusts the intra- and intermolecular connections and softens the target molecules. It was revealed that these ILs show good photoluminescent properties both in bulk solutions and in solvent-free states, enabling them to be used as a new generation of photoluminescent inks (Fig. 18
                     ). Two novel FILs based 1-(2-methoxyethyl)-3-methylimidazolium [MOEMIm][Ln(NO3)4] (Ln =Eu, Dy) was introduced by Guan and co-workers that emit bright red (Eu3+) and light blue (Dy3+) photoluminescence under UV light irradiation, and employed for the detection of explosive nitro aromatics compounds by fluorescence quenching mechanism [190]. A new generation of PL inks was also developed by Li co-workers [191] based on carbon QDs-RTILs hybrids composite and its compatibility with various writing tools was demonstrated.
